solutions.content:
There are 7 valid states and 1 valid state. Each state has a next function to advance to the next state base on the current character. At each state, if we get an unexpected character, we should move the State.INVALID.
The code is pretty self explanatory.
Only think need to take care of is after looping through all the characters in the input. We have to make sure that the current state is not at an invalid ending state. Invalid ending states are INIT, SIGN, DOT, and EXPONENT which are corresponding to ending with "empty", "+/-", ".", "e/E".
May not be the most optimized code, but easy to read and understand.
```
class Solution {
    public enum State {
        INIT {
            @Override
            public State next(char c) {
                if ('0' <= c && c <= '9') return INTEGER;
                if (c == '+' || c == '-') return SIGN;
                if (c == '.') return DOT;
                return INVALID;
            }
            @Override
            public boolean isValid() {
                return false;
            }
        },
        SIGN {
            @Override
            public State next(char c) {
                if ('0' <= c && c <= '9') return INTEGER;
                if (c == '.') return DOT;
                return INVALID;
            }
            @Override
            public boolean isValid() {
                return false;
            }
        },
        DOT {
