Hi , everybody. Today's question is not based on any standard algorithm. We can say that it is to be solved with a greedy approach. But , I would personally think that it is more implementation based. 

But , honestly , this question is **really easy**. It is a good practice for loops and string traversals , but it should not be considered for interview prep or for DSA . 

**Anyways, moving to the point, the question says that the string represents a particular version. We have to evaluate that version numerically and then compare 2 such versions to return whether they are equal or less than or greater than.**

There are no multiple approaches to this question. 

### APPROACH : 
How do we approach this question ??
Well , lets take an example. 
**V1= "23.78.43.0.0.0" and V2= "23.78.043.0.001"**
Now , in order to compare any versions is like comparing 2 words in a dictionary , for every character in the words,  we check which character comes first lexicographically . The one that comes first appears earlier in the dictionary. 
Similarly , we compare every revision in the 2 versions. 
In the above example , 
**1st REVISION :**
**V1 --> 23  and V2 --> 23**
*Both of them are same so , till now both of the versions are placed in the same position in the dictionary.*

**2nd REVISION :**
**V1 --> 78  and V2 --> 78**
*Both of them are same so , till now both of the versions are placed in the same position in the dictionary.*

**3rd REVISION :**
**V1 --> 43  and V2 --> 043 ~ 43**
*Both of them are same so , till now both of the versions are placed in the same position in the dictionary.*

**4th REVISION :**
**V1 --> 0  and V2 --> 0**
*Both of them are same so , till now both of the versions are placed in the same position in the dictionary.*

**5th REVISION :**
**V1 --> 0  and V2 --> 001 ~1**
*Now in this revision , **VERSION_2** has a higher score, so **VERSION_1 WILL BE PLACED BEFORE VERSION_2** in the dictionary.*

So , the result is **V1<V2**. 


### SOLUTION : 
1. Compare every revision of the 2 versions .
2. If the **current revisions are the same** , **continue to compare**. 
3. If the **currentRevision_V1 < currentRevision_V2** , **return -1 . Else return 1**. 
4. After all the revisions , if nothing is returned , **return 0 ( as both the versions are same by now )** 

### CODE : 

#### Sorry , for all the long variable names. It is done to make the code more understandable. The code is 100% faster than other submissions, though.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/9a6011b3-43e0-4da6-be11-4ebc74e015bd_1645750377.4996574.png)

```
class Solution {
public:
    int compareVersion(string version1, string version2) {

        int scoreV1=0,scoreV2=0,i,j,currentVersionScore=0;
        i=j=0;
        while(i<version1.size() or j<version2.size())
        {
            // finding the score of the current revision of version 1
            currentVersionScore=0;
            while(i<version1.size() and version1[i]!='.')
            {
                currentVersionScore=currentVersionScore*10+(version1[i]-'0');
                i++;
            }
            scoreV1+=currentVersionScore;

            //finding the score of the current revision of version 2
            currentVersionScore=0;
            while(j<version2.size() and version2[j]!='.')
            {
                currentVersionScore=currentVersionScore*10+(version2[j]-'0');
                j++;
            }
            scoreV2+=currentVersionScore;

			// I am converting each VERSION into a score (to compare it lexicographically just as mentioned in the approach)

            if(scoreV1<scoreV2)
                return -1;
            else if(scoreV1>scoreV2)
                return 1;
            i++;
            j++;
        }

        return 0;

    }
};

```

**TC : O(M+N)**
**SC : O(1)**

