# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The code aims to compare two version strings by splitting them into individual components (separated by periods) and comparing each corresponding component numerically.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Split the version1 and version2 strings into arrays of components using the period as the delimiter. Store the components in arr1 and arr2 arrays, respectively.
2. Initialize a variable i as 0 to iterate through the components of arr1 and arr2.
3. While i is less than the length of arr1 or arr2, perform the following comparisons:
- If both arr1 and arr2 have components at index i, compare the numerical values of the components.
1. If arr1[i] is less than arr2[i], return -1 to indicate that version1 is smaller than version2.
2. If arr1[i] is greater than arr2[i], return 1 to indicate that version1 is greater than version2.
- If arr1 still has components remaining (i.e., i is within the bounds of arr1), check if the remaining components are non-zero.
1. If a non-zero component is found, return 1 to indicate that version1 is greater than version2.
- If arr2 still has components remaining (i.e., i is within the bounds of arr2), check if the remaining components are non-zero.
1. If a non-zero component is found, return -1 to indicate that version1 is smaller than version2.
- Increment i to move to the next component.
4. If the loop completes without any return statements, it means both versions are equal. Return 0 to indicate equality.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the code is O(max(n, m)), where n is the number of components in version1 and m is the number of components in version2. The code iterates through the components of the versions until either arr1 or arr2 is exhausted or a difference is found. The maximum number of iterations is determined by the larger number of components between the two versions.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of the code is O(max(n, m)), where n is the number of components in version1 and m is the number of components in version2. It is due to the storage of the components in the arr1 and arr2 arrays. The space required for other variables and temporary values is negligible compared to the size of the input strings.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int compareVersion(String version1, String version2) {
        String[] arr1 = version1.split("\\.");
        String[] arr2 = version2.split("\\.");
        int i=0;
        while(i<arr1.length || i<arr2.length)
        {
            if(i<arr1.length && i<arr2.length)
            {
                if(Integer.parseInt(arr1[i]) < Integer.parseInt(arr2[i]))
                {
                    return -1;
                }
                else if(Integer.parseInt(arr1[i]) > Integer.parseInt(arr2[i]))
                {
                    return 1;
                }
            }
            else if(i<arr1.length)
            {
                if(Integer.parseInt(arr1[i]) != 0)
                {
                    return 1;
                }
            } 
            else if(i<arr2.length)
            {
                if(Integer.parseInt(arr2[i]) != 0)
                {
                    return -1;
                }
            }
            i++;
        }
        return 0;
    }
}
```

