# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
This solution uses a breadth-first search (BFS) algorithm to check if it is possible to measure exactly targetCapacity liters of water using the two jugs with capacities jug1Capacity and jug2Capacity.

The algorithm starts by adding the initial state of the jugs, both with 0 liters of water, to a queue. Then, it repeatedly removes the next state from the queue, checks if it has been visited before, and performs the following operations:

If the current state of the jugs contains exactly targetCapacity liters of water, the algorithm returns true.
If the current state of the jugs has not been visited before, it adds it to the visited set.
Then, the algorithm generates the next possible states of the jugs by:
- Filling jug1 with water.
- Filling jug2 with water.
- Emptying jug1.
- Emptying jug2.
- Pouring water from jug1 to jug2 until jug2 is full or jug1 is empty
- Pouring water from jug2 to jug1 until jug1 is full or jug2 is empty.
    Finally, if the queue is empty, the algorithm returns false, indicating that it is not possible to measure exactly targetCapacity liters of water using the two jugs.

This solution uses a queue to keep track of the next states to be visited, and a set to keep track of the visited states, in order to avoid visiting the same state multiple times, which helps to improve the performance of the algorithm.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public boolean canMeasureWater(int jug1Capacity, int jug2Capacity, int targetCapacity) {
        Queue<List<Integer>> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        queue.add(Arrays.asList(0, 0));

        Set<List<Integer>> visited = new HashSet<>();
        while(!queue.isEmpty()){
            List<Integer> values = queue.poll();
            if(visited.contains(values)){
                continue;
            }
            int jug1 = values.get(0);
            int jug2 = values.get(1);
            visited.add(values);

            if(Stream.of(jug1, jug2, jug1 + jug2, jug1 + jug2Capacity, jug2Capacity + jug1).anyMatch(v->v==targetCapacity))
                return true;

            queue.add(Arrays.asList(Math.min(jug2 + jug1, jug1Capacity), 0));
            queue.add(Arrays.asList(0, Math.min(jug2 + jug1, jug2Capacity)));
            queue.add(Arrays.asList(Math.abs(jug2Capacity - jug1), 0));
            queue.add(Arrays.asList(0, Math.abs(jug1Capacity - jug2)));
        }

        return false;
    }
}
```

