To solve this problem, a special theory is needed, I don't know its name though. (lol)

Theory:
If positive integer A and B are coprime, then we have:
(A * k) % B = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ... B-1, if k could be any positive integer.

In this specific question, let's assume the jug A's capacity to be x and jug B's capacity to be y. 

# Circumstance 1: x and y are coprime
Since x and y are coprime, they must be unequal. WIthout loss of generality, let's say x < y, i.e. x <= y - 1. 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/77fe13cd-d614-40db-ba7e-5596cbcc0a1c_1626081016.3956423.png)

Firstly we fill up jug A and pour the water into B, now A contains 0 unit of water and B contains x units of water.
water inside B = x * 1
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/62c28220-ba7d-4561-acb8-e3b10add1658_1626081049.747994.png)



Then we fill up A again and pour all the water into B, now A is empty but B has 2 \* x water in it. 
water inside B = x * 2
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e097da3d-676c-4207-9e26-e6c96f610eae_1626080936.4572258.png)





Repeat the aforemention process, there's must be some time when A couldn't pour all the water into B because B is full, say it is the i-th time. 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/626dacfa-765e-4122-9262-849433b4129c_1626081132.1597867.png)

When this siituation occurs, empty container B, and move water in A to B. Now we have:
water inside B = (x * i) % y
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7d065d71-ba83-4835-a18f-f0e5998f9926_1626081258.3175855.png)



We may have found that the amount of water inside B always meets the equation:
water inside B = (x * some integer) % y.

According to the theory i mentioned, the water inside B cound be any integers in range [0, y - 1]. In other words, we can reach any value within [0, y -1]. If we fill A again, we can get any amount within [x, y-1+x]. Notice that x <= y - 1, after union the two ranges we got [0, y-1+x]. Actually, if we fill up both A and B we got x+y units of water, which expands the range into [0, x+y].

Now we can confidently say that if gcd(x,y) = 1, (gcd - greatest common divisor), we can get any amount of water equal or less than x+y units.  

# Circumstance 2: x and y are not coprime
This time gcd(x , y) = k > 1. 
One thing is quite clear, we cannot reach a target which couldn't be divide by k! For example, if you're given x = 6, y = 9, then you cannot get z if z%3 != 0. 
If the target is divisible by k, then why don't we refactor all the numbers, i.e. x, y , target, since they have a common divisor?
We do : x = x / k,  y = y / k, target = target / k. After that you would notice that x and y are coprime again, which leads us to circumstance 1.

This is my code if you need:

```
class Solution {
public:
    int getGCD(int a,int b){
        if(a>b)
            swap(a,b);
        while((b%=a)!=0){
            if(a>b)
                swap(a,b);
        }
        return a; 
    }
    bool canMeasureWater(int jug1Capacity, int jug2Capacity, int targetCapacity) {
        int GCD= getGCD(jug1Capacity, jug2Capacity);
        jug1Capacity /= GCD;
        jug2Capacity /= GCD;
        if((targetCapacity%GCD) != 0)
            return false;
        return (targetCapacity/GCD <= jug1Capacity + jug2Capacity);

    }
};
```

