Technically, this is a bit of a mix of both. Every possible combination of numbers between both the jugs could be represented in the bigger jug. So, we will keep putitng quantities from the second jug into the first jug to get different possible quantites and track the quantites through the visited array. So all we need to do is check for the edge cases as in the lines 
```
if (c_y < 0) {
                int remainder = c_y + x;
                c_y+=y;
                if (c_y+remainder == z || y + remainder == z) return true;
            }
```

Here is a sample iteration:

Say we have jug_1 = 3 and jug_2 = 5.
Then, on iteration 1:
jug_1 = 0, jug_2 = 5
iteration 2:
jug_1 = 0, jug_2 = 5-3 = 2 --> pour this into jug_1 and fill up jug_2 to the top again and put 1 litre back into jug_1
iteration 3: 
jug_1 = 2, jug_2 = 4 // because we can pour 1 litre into jug_1 from previous iteration

jug_2 = 4 so the solution is true.

At every point, we will record the current_y value if it is visited before into the visited array since solutions that are already visited will give the similar answers to before and do not need to be computed again.

```
public boolean canMeasureWater(int x, int y, int z) {
        if (z > x+y) return false;
        if (z == x || z == y || z == 0 || z == x+y) return true;
        //make y the bigger one
        if (x > y) {
            int temp = x;
            x = y;
            y = temp;
        }
        int c_y = y; //current_y
        boolean[] visited = new boolean[x+y+1];
        while (c_y != z) {
            if (visited[c_y]) return false;
            visited[c_y] = true;
            c_y-=x;
            if (c_y < 0) {
                int remainder = c_y + x;
                c_y+=y;
                if (c_y+remainder == z || y + remainder == z) return true;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
