For this question, the math way to solve it is GCD (Greatest common divisior), but it is not easy to come up with within 20 mins. So my first solution is DFS which try every possible moves but it cannot pass some test cases under x, y are quite large but z is quite small.
```
class Solution {
    // I used a status to track the status of two different containers.
    class Status {
        int containY, containX;
        public Status(int A, int B) {
            containX = A;
            containY = B;
        }

        public int getSum() {
            return containX + containY;
        }

        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            int hash = 5;
            hash = 17 * hash + this.containX + this.containY;
            return hash;
        }

        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object other) {
            if (other == null || getClass() != other.getClass()) {
                return false;
            }
            else {
                Status o = (Status)other;
                return this.containX == o.containX && this.containY == o.containY;
            }
        }
    }

    HashSet<Status> statuses = new HashSet<Status>();
    public boolean canMeasureWater(int x, int y, int z) {
        return dfs(x, y, new Status(0, 0), z);
    }

    public boolean dfs(int x, int y, Status s, int z) {
        if (s.getSum() == z) {
            return true;
        }
        else if (statuses.contains(s)) {
            return false;
        }
        else {
            statuses.add(s);
            Status thisS;
            // Pull into A
            thisS = new Status(x, s.containY);
            if (dfs(x, y, thisS, z))
                return true;
            // Pull into B
            thisS = new Status(s.containX, y);
            if (dfs(x, y, thisS, z))
                return true;
            // Pull A to B
            thisS = new Status(s.containX-Math.min(y-s.containY, s.containX), s.containY + Math.min(y-s.containY, s.containX));
            if (dfs(x, y, thisS, z))
                return true;
            // Pull B to A
            thisS = new Status(s.containX+Math.min(x-s.containX, s.containY), s.containY - Math.min(x-s.containX, s.containY));
            if (dfs(x, y, thisS, z))
                return true;
            // Pull out A
            thisS = new Status(0, s.containY);
            if (dfs(x, y, thisS, z))
                return true;
            // Pull out B
            thisS = new Status(s.containX, 0);
            if (dfs(x, y, thisS, z))
                return true;

            return false;
        }
    }
}
```

Then I come up with another solution: Instead of tracking all possible moves, I tracked all possible values we could get from 2 jugs. For example 3 and 5. We could get 0, 3, 5, 2, ..., 4 and I use queue to track the last value we could get and a HashSet to track the value we already have checked. 

The edge case is that `there is no way for both of jugs are not full and not empty.` In other word, for the given example 3 & 5, there is no way for the first container has 1 liter and second container has 2 liter.

Here is explanation:
There are in total 6 ways for us to move:
1. Fill in x -> x is full
2. Fill in y -> y is full
3. Pull water out of x -> x is emp
4. Pull water out of y -> y is emp
5. Pull water from x to y -> x is emp or y is full
6. Pull water from y to x -> y is emp or x is full

HEre is my BFS solution (Passed):
```
class Solution {
    public boolean canMeasureWater(int x, int y, int z) {
        // BFS to find all the possible liters we could get from the given two jugs.
        if (x > y) {
            // In order to simplify the problem, I let y always bigger than x's size
            int hold = x;
            x = y;
            y = hold;
        }
        HashSet<Integer> all = new HashSet<>();
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        q.offer(0);
        while (!q.isEmpty()) {
            int size = q.size();
            for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                int last = q.poll();
                if (!all.contains(last) && last >= 0) {
                    if (last == z)
                        return true;
                    all.add(last);
                    if (last <= x) {
                        q.offer(last + y);
                        q.offer(x + last);
                        q.offer(y - (x - last));
                        q.offer(x - (y - last));
                    }
                    else if (last <= y) {
                        q.offer(x + last);
                        q.offer(x - (y - last));
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}

